 and system architecture overviews.
 Reference Documentation entries do not prescribe action steps and are not subject to the structured procedure format requirement in Section 6.3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Ownership and review obligations for each category shall follow the roles defined in Section 3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Structured Procedure Format
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All KB procedures shall document tasks as discrete,
 sequentially numbered steps.
 Procedures shall address known error conditions and their corresponding recovery actions as conditional branches within the step sequence.
 Procedures shall specify the expected end state upon successful completion.
 The formatting conventions and templates implementing this requirement are operational decisions established and maintained by the Assistant IT Director.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Standard Change Authorization Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
A KB procedure qualifies a change type as Standard only when it carries explicit IT Director approval.
 If no qualifying KB procedure exists,
 the change shall be classified as Significant.
 Retirement or material modification of any Standard change procedure shall require the same IT Director approval path as creation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Known Error Entry Lifecycle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Known Error entries are a distinct KB record type.
 Upon Known Error declaration,
 the Assistant IT Director shall ensure publication within two (2) business days,
 including symptoms,
 workaround procedure,
 and Problem record reference.
 Upon permanent remediation and Problem closure,
